00:02:35.339 --> 00:02:42.259
So, coming from that background, I went to Brigham Young University in Provo, Utah for

00:02:42.259 --> 00:02:46.300
my undergraduate degree, which was in mathematics education.

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:49.820
My original plan was to be a high school math teacher.

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:55.139
And then, through the course of some events, I ended up getting into statistics.

00:02:55.139 --> 00:03:00.339
The master's program there at BYU in the statistics program and absolutely loved it.

00:03:00.339 --> 00:03:05.899
And then, took that opportunity to then go on to do a PhD in statistics and that was

00:03:05.899 --> 00:03:07.899
at Virginia Tech in Blacksburg, Virginia.

00:03:07.899 --> 00:03:11.220
So, hopefully, there's some Hokies or some Cougars out there.

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:16.339
If you are, give a thumbs up for those alumni.

00:03:16.339 --> 00:03:22.380
The stats program at Virginia Tech is the third oldest statistics program in the country.

00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:25.419
And so, it has a really long history.

00:03:25.419 --> 00:03:30.300
And the area of my dissertation research was in the area of multivariable statistical process

00:03:30.300 --> 00:03:33.619
control, which comes actually full circle.

00:03:33.619 --> 00:03:37.539
I'll talk a little bit about some work that we're doing in the area of manufacturing and

00:03:37.539 --> 00:03:40.500
using Posit to help us there as well.

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.580
So, a little bit around the work experience journey.

00:03:44.580 --> 00:03:50.779
After graduating with my PhD, started to work at GE General Electric in their research headquarters.

00:03:50.779 --> 00:03:54.020
This was in upstate New York and really loved it there.

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:56.660
GE, at the time, owned a little bit of everything.

00:03:56.660 --> 00:04:01.979
And so, you think about, you know, GE, you know, it's not just kind of light bulbs and,

00:04:01.979 --> 00:04:07.300
you know, dishwashers and things like that, but, you know, they used to have this large

00:04:07.339 --> 00:04:09.259
capital financial business.

00:04:09.259 --> 00:04:14.699
So, we would, you know, lean loans and leases of all kinds of equipment.

00:04:14.699 --> 00:04:17.619
So, that's where I got into the area of financial services.

00:04:17.619 --> 00:04:21.100
And that led to a role with JPMorgan Chase and their analytics headquarters.

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:24.579
And that was actually in Columbus, Ohio.

00:04:24.579 --> 00:04:26.859
So, moved the family to Ohio and was there for a couple years.

00:04:26.859 --> 00:04:32.100
And that's where I really learned the concept of big data.

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:40.540
And by the way, this is like 2010, it's kind of timeframe, big data and just really, you

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:44.140
know, using vast amounts of data to make decision making.

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:49.260
And the banking, the financial industry, I feel like has been kind of well ahead in the

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:50.500
analytics curve.

00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:57.859
You know, for example, at JPMorgan Chase, I never heard of anything in terms of an analytics

00:04:57.859 --> 00:04:59.019
project.

00:04:59.019 --> 00:05:00.980
It was just the way things were.

00:05:00.980 --> 00:05:03.700
It was part of the DNA of the company.

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:10.100
Whereas when I took my next role at Dow AgroSciences, I was asked to come and start up a

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:12.339
brand new business analytics team.

00:05:12.339 --> 00:05:14.459
So, I went and hired a small team.

00:05:14.459 --> 00:05:20.420
And really, we were just starting from scratch and trying to get analytics use cases going.

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:26.540
And everything was in terms of project and use cases and just trying to get momentum and get

00:05:26.540 --> 00:05:28.859
buy-in from various stakeholders.

00:05:28.899 --> 00:05:33.779
Whereas where I'd come from a place where there was no major decision made unless the

00:05:33.779 --> 00:05:35.739
analytics team signed off on it.

00:05:35.739 --> 00:05:39.660
And it was such an integral part of how decisions were made.

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:44.059
So, it was quite a learning experience and to go to a place where we had to sort of prove

00:05:44.059 --> 00:05:45.380
ourselves.

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:50.500
And so, the Dow AgroSciences role took me and my family here to Indianapolis, Indiana.

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:52.140
Now, Dow AgroSciences doesn't exist.

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:55.779
So, Dow and DuPont merged to become Corteva.

00:05:55.779 --> 00:06:00.019
And that was happening while I was there.

00:06:00.019 --> 00:06:02.500
I had a really great experience with Dow.

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:06.940
And then here in Indianapolis is the headquarters for Eli Lilly.

00:06:06.940 --> 00:06:15.100
And I had the opportunity to come into Lilly and basically take an advanced analytics team

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:21.940
of PhDs in statistics and operations research, et cetera, and grow that team and expand it

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:30.420
across the globe to be not just U.S. centered, but also Japan, China, Europe, et cetera,

00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:35.220
and as well as expand our different types of work we're doing within the U.S.

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:42.220
So, really great opportunity to work and learn in a highly regulated space of how analytics

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:44.140
can make a difference.

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:50.500
And then two years ago, this is during the pandemic, so February of 2021, I had the opportunity

00:06:50.540 --> 00:06:58.179
to come here at Zoetis with just an amazing opportunity to basically create and lead a

00:06:58.179 --> 00:07:02.380
brand new business insights and analytics team.

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:06.660
And so, basically, I was given like a blank sheet of paper to draw the organizational

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:11.500
design, write the job descriptions, and go and hire the team to accomplish the vision

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:16.179
of leading in digital and data analytics, which is one of the company priorities that's

00:07:16.179 --> 00:07:18.899
been publicly stated.

00:07:18.899 --> 00:07:23.299
And just recently, that priority was reworded slightly to be now we're going to power the

00:07:23.299 --> 00:07:28.339
business through digital and data analytics capabilities, so really, really happy about

00:07:28.339 --> 00:07:29.339
that.

00:07:29.339 --> 00:07:33.500
So, I'll come back and talk a little bit more about the team, but kind of finishing the

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:35.420
story here.

