So, anyway, we're in that phase right now.

00:07:56.619 --> 00:08:01.140
And I also, you know, for fun, I've competed in things like, you know, Ironman triathlons.

00:08:01.140 --> 00:08:03.100
I've completed six of those.

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:08.660
I've qualified for and completed and competed in the Boston Marathon as well.

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:10.619
That was an amazing experience.

00:08:10.619 --> 00:08:17.619
Took me more than 10 years of effort to actually go and qualify to be able to run into Boston,

00:08:17.619 --> 00:08:21.260
which is a whole story in and of itself of how I use data and analytics to help me get

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:22.260
there, which is so cool.

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:27.459
So, maybe if we have time later on, we can talk about how data analytics helped me to

00:08:27.459 --> 00:08:31.940
facilitate improving to get to where I can qualify for Boston.

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:36.099
And back in college, this is when I was at BYU as an undergrad, I was a former competitive

00:08:36.099 --> 00:08:37.099
ballroom dancer.

00:08:37.099 --> 00:08:38.739
You can see from that picture there.

00:08:38.859 --> 00:08:45.500
I was having way too much fun, as you can tell, as an undergrad on the ballroom dance team.

00:08:45.500 --> 00:08:51.500
And also, when I was between my freshman and sophomore years of college, I took a two-year

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:55.020
leave of absence to serve a mission for my church.

00:08:55.020 --> 00:08:59.739
And in these types of situations, we are not, we don't get to choose where we go or what

00:08:59.739 --> 00:09:00.739
language we speak.

00:09:00.739 --> 00:09:05.739
And I was asked to go to Argentina, so live there for two years and learn to speak Spanish.

00:09:05.739 --> 00:09:11.859
Entonces, si algunas personas se hablan Español, podemos hablar Español después.

00:09:11.859 --> 00:09:15.979
So I learned a little bit Spanish there and try to keep that up a little bit every day.

00:09:15.979 --> 00:09:20.260
So that's a little bit about me and my background, and to kind of go through the team a little

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:21.260
bit.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:25.539
So, but before I jump into that, any questions that pop up, I'm going to talk through kind

00:09:25.539 --> 00:09:30.340
of the genesis of the team and kind of the org structure and how we work.

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:31.340
Any questions?

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:32.340
I can't tell.

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:37.020
There is an anonymous question that I think is exactly what you're talking about.

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:41.979
The question is, how do you go about building a data science team from scratch?

00:09:41.979 --> 00:09:42.979
Great question.

00:09:42.979 --> 00:09:44.539
So that's exactly what we had to do here.

00:09:44.539 --> 00:09:45.539
Wasn't planned.

00:09:45.539 --> 00:09:46.539
Yeah.

00:09:46.539 --> 00:09:47.539
Yeah.

00:09:47.539 --> 00:09:49.419
So I've had to do this twice now.

00:09:49.419 --> 00:09:51.179
This is the second time.

00:09:51.179 --> 00:09:55.580
The first time was when I was brought into Dow AgriSciences, and that was a much smaller

00:09:55.580 --> 00:10:00.659
team, smaller scope that was just for the commercial kind of scope.

00:10:00.659 --> 00:10:07.500
In this case, Zoetis is, just a little bit of background on the company, Zoetis is the

00:10:07.500 --> 00:10:10.940
largest animal health company in the world.

00:10:10.940 --> 00:10:17.299
So it's an $8 billion company with 13,000 or so employees globally.

00:10:17.299 --> 00:10:22.940
So if any of you have dogs or cats, then very likely there's a chance that your dogs or

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:28.780
cats are being prescribed Zoetis medications from your veterinarian, or any of you are

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:30.820
associated with livestock farming.

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:37.140
So cattle, beef or dairy cattle, pigs, chickens, sheep, and even salmon.

00:10:37.140 --> 00:10:38.820
So fish farming as well.

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:43.659
We have products to help to serve those animals.

00:10:43.659 --> 00:10:51.940
So a little bit about the company, and it's really great to be in this place where our

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:57.640
mission is to help improve the world by improving the health of animals.

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:04.039
Those that are companion animals, as well as those that are used to help feed the world.

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:10.679
So in 2020, we had a new CEO, Kristen Peck, that took the helm.

00:11:10.679 --> 00:11:15.000
And one of the first changes she does was to bring in a new chief information officer

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:16.960
who is Wafa Mamili.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:22.440
And I had known and worked with Wafa at Eli Lilly previously, and she is just an absolutely

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:23.840
spectacular leader.

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:29.919
You can go and Google Wafa Mamili afterwards and read all about all the words and the great

00:11:29.919 --> 00:11:31.960
leader that she is, as well as Kristen.

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:37.960
So Wafa came in and completely took a new direction into the company to be technology

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:38.960
and digital focused.

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:43.440
And that's where the priority of leading in digital and data analytics came about.

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:48.520
And that was really the foundation of why my team was created and funding it.

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:49.520
So not just words.

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:55.700
We don't say, hey, by words we're supporting you, but actually by dollars and resources.

00:11:55.700 --> 00:12:03.080
And so I was brought in along with others to build this data, this business insights

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:04.080
and analytics team.

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:10.440
And so one of my first responsibilities was to understand what the business needs are

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:14.000
and to understand how we can play a role in that.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:19.119
And when I came in, I realized that there were some data scientists and pockets of data

00:12:19.719 --> 00:12:23.000
science throughout the company, mainly in our U.S. commercial, which is our major commercial

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:28.440
unit, as well as in our R&D group, there were data science statisticians, et cetera, in

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:29.440
those areas.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:34.359
And so we didn't want to focus on those areas at first because we knew there was already

00:12:34.359 --> 00:12:36.520
ongoing work there and support.

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:42.919
And so what we did was design the organization to be one where we had dedicated focus of

00:12:42.919 --> 00:12:44.000
data analysts.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:49.919
So those that are not necessarily have master's and PhDs in data science, but have bachelor's

00:12:49.919 --> 00:12:56.799
or so forth degrees in data analytics type of degree areas that we can focus in particular

00:12:56.799 --> 00:12:57.799
areas.

00:12:57.799 --> 00:13:03.119
And then I designed a pool of data scientists that could then be deployed across any of

00:13:03.119 --> 00:13:08.479
the use cases and could be very flexible kind of a pool there.

00:13:08.479 --> 00:13:13.599
And so we focused a lot of our initial work in the area of manufacturing and supply chain

00:13:13.599 --> 00:13:18.960
as well as our international commercial business, where there was very little or none in terms

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:21.359
of data science support.

00:13:21.359 --> 00:13:28.520
And so they were immediately, there's so much pent up demand in these spaces that it didn't

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:30.880
take long for us to generate momentum in those areas.

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:34.880
Then we also did things like with finance and HR kind of other enabling functions, but

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:38.960
we focused mainly on our manufacturing supply chain and our international commercial.

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:45.039
And as we gain momentum, we've expanded now to more use cases within the U.S. commercial

00:13:45.039 --> 00:13:48.119
as well as in our R&D space.

00:13:48.119 --> 00:13:52.520
So in terms of designing the organization, I basically just designed to have an analytical

00:13:52.520 --> 00:13:53.520
lead.

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:54.520
So an analytics lead.

00:13:54.520 --> 00:13:58.679
So an analytic lead that I see as a person who's a translator between what are the needs

00:13:58.679 --> 00:14:02.119
of the business and what are the analytic solutions that can help to solve those needs.

00:14:02.119 --> 00:14:06.039
So someone that understands analytics very well, but also understands the business problem

00:14:06.039 --> 00:14:07.039
that can do that translation.

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:11.960
So I have analytics leads for each of those areas, and then data analysts that report

00:14:11.960 --> 00:14:16.599
to them, and this pool of data scientists that work across all of those verticals to

00:14:16.599 --> 00:14:21.280
serve the needs across each of those areas.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:24.400
So that's a little bit about the org design and what we came up with.

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:28.840
And then it was just going about hiring the team, writing the job descriptions.

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:33.440
I see, just kind of to take a quick glance here, I see Catalina Moreno, I'm going to

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:34.440
call her out.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:37.080
She is one of our top and excellent senior data scientists.

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:39.320
So kudos to Catalina.

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:42.520
What I'll talk about a little bit later are some of the really great work that she has

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:43.520
helped to build.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:46.520
So I'm really grateful to have her here.

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:49.679
If there's other, so what is data scientists are on the call that I'm missing as I'm scanning

00:14:49.679 --> 00:14:53.900
through, I apologize for that.

00:14:53.900 --> 00:14:56.799
So hiring the team was the next thing.

00:14:56.799 --> 00:14:58.919
And that took several months to do that.

00:14:59.119 --> 00:15:04.960
One of the key factors for us was being able to be flexible in terms of location.

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:09.159
I don't know how many of you are considered to be remote employees, but I was hired in

00:15:09.159 --> 00:15:12.880
during the pandemic and I was told, look, you're in Indianapolis, but we're a New Jersey

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:13.880
based headquarters.

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:18.479
We want you to be in New Jersey if you want to, but you don't have to.

00:15:18.479 --> 00:15:21.780
And so I said, well, I think we're going to stay here and they're like, okay, great.

00:15:21.780 --> 00:15:23.599
So you're remote now.

00:15:24.039 --> 00:15:30.479
So when I hired the team, it was always a remote option if they wanted to stay remote.

00:15:30.479 --> 00:15:34.400
Some of them wanted to be able to go into the office at times.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:40.559
But that was really the key to be able to recruit people from all over the globe, actually.

00:15:40.559 --> 00:15:47.500
So not just in the US, but leave that flexibility for remote work.

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:53.320
And so basically all of our meetings every day are virtual, which, you know, there's

00:15:54.039 --> 00:15:56.119
a lot of pros or some cons to that.

00:15:56.119 --> 00:15:57.119
A lot of flexibility.

00:15:57.119 --> 00:16:01.239
We do miss that kind of face-to-face interaction.

