00:37:24.439 --> 00:37:36.439
And that was the first step. Once they identified those, then we did the second step, which is feasibility, where we took a little bit of time to gather the data to, to look at the, the data available.

00:37:36.439 --> 00:37:46.439
Do we have enough data and the right kind of data to do a proof of concept? And if so, then we went to the next stage, which was proof of concept. And here's where we would build.

00:37:47.439 --> 00:38:03.439
You know, it's, it's, we're talking, the ideal would be between two and four weeks quick proof of concept using the data that we have sort of in a sandbox or offline. We're not building production ready code. We're not building something that's ready to go, to go live. We're just trying to prove the value.

00:38:03.439 --> 00:38:12.439
So that's really the idea of a proof of concept. Two things. Can we do it? And does it have the value? Those are the two questions we're trying to answer with a proof of concept.

00:38:13.439 --> 00:38:19.439
And if the answer to both of those is yes, there's real business value and we were successfully able to do it.

00:38:19.439 --> 00:38:36.439
Then we go to the fourth stage, which is the pilot. And that's where we would make it more production ready. Here's where we were going to, you know, partner with our data engineering team to take the analytic solution and put it into production on a small scale.

00:38:37.439 --> 00:38:53.439
And think of it as, you know, maybe one manufacturing site, one line, you know, kind of thing where you're not scaling it across, you know, many different places, but, but being more deliberate in how you do it. And this is a, this thing, it's kind of a risk based approach.

00:38:54.439 --> 00:39:06.439
And we were given permission to fail. A lot of the proof of concepts succeeded. There were some that did not. Some, or some succeeded, but maybe didn't have as much value as we anticipated. They were good, but maybe not as high.

00:39:07.439 --> 00:39:27.439
And so focusing on those highest value proof of concepts going on to the next stage of piloting. And then those, those pilots that are successful. For example, the, what I talked about the monoclonal antibody is very successful. We want to scale that to other, other sites, other products, other stages of the process.

00:39:28.439 --> 00:39:39.439
And, you know, leverage what we learned there and scale it across other areas. And so that's that scale up, you know, stage, which would be after the stage five is scale up after piloting.

00:39:40.439 --> 00:39:58.439
And the last stage is once we scaled it up as sustaining. So how do we sustain the value long-term? And so those six stages are kind of how we thought about it up front. And as a team, you know, we had, we had the team size, but also some, some resources for partner support.

00:39:58.439 --> 00:40:16.439
So we had also some consulting, you know, support to help us scale faster. And within the first year or so of us getting started, the total number of use cases in our, in our, in our use case tracker was about a hundred in various of those six stages.

00:40:16.439 --> 00:40:35.439
You know, some, some were just ideas, some were, you know, being, you know, prioritized somewhere in the feasibility step, some of the proof of concept, et cetera. So, but from there now we've taken the most high value of those, and we're actually focusing more on those and how we can pilot them and scale them.

